    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4da7a705-32ac-493c-bc65-0f53e700b15a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 78-year-old retired high school mathematics teacher who appears slightly older than his stated age, with a thin build and a soft, masked facial expression. He moves carefully and slowly, taking short shuffling steps and needing a moment to rise from a chair. A faint resting tremor is noticeable in his right hand, especially when he is distracted, and his voice is quiet and somewhat monotone. He is neatly dressed, values routine, and is usually accompanied to appointments by his wife, who helps him keep track of medications and transportation.\n\nOver the last several years, {patientName} has developed increasing slowness of movement, stiffness in his shoulders and legs, reduced arm swing, and intermittent balance difficulty, especially when turning. He reports constipation, reduced sense of smell, and fragmented sleep with vivid dreams. He has also noticed that writing has become smaller and more cramped, and family members say his facial expression has become less animated. He denies frank hallucinations but admits to occasional mild forgetfulness and frustration over his declining independence.\n\n{patientName} lives with his wife in a single-story home and remains engaged in daily activities, though at a slower pace. He enjoys gardening, listening to jazz, and meeting a small group of retired friends for coffee once a week. He no longer drives long distances because of slowed reaction time. He uses a cane outdoors and has had one non-injurious fall in the past year. He is a former smoker who quit decades ago and drinks alcohol only occasionally.\n\nHe has two adult children who live nearby and visit regularly. His family describes him as thoughtful, disciplined, and proud of maintaining as much autonomy as possible. He tries to stay active with short neighborhood walks and a community exercise class for seniors, but symptoms of bradykinesia and fatigue increasingly interfere with his hobbies and social confidence."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9d045c49-f493-4031-968e-45a697f8c4bc",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has experienced gradually progressive motor slowing and right-sided resting tremor over approximately 4 years, with more noticeable gait instability in the last 12 months. He reports stiffness worse in the morning, increasing difficulty with buttons and handwriting, and occasional near-freezing when turning in narrow spaces. Constipation has been present for several years, and his wife reports dream enactment behaviors during sleep. He has not had prior stroke symptoms, seizure history, or exposure to dopamine-blocking antipsychotic medications.\n\nPast medical history includes essential hypertension, benign prostatic hyperplasia, chronic constipation, and bilateral knee osteoarthritis. He was hospitalized once 3 years ago for community-acquired pneumonia and recovered fully. There is no history of major head trauma. He had one mechanical fall six months ago while stepping off a curb, without fracture or loss of consciousness.\n\n{patientName} is a former smoker with an estimated 20 pack-year history, having quit at age 52. He drinks 1-2 alcoholic beverages per week and denies illicit drug use. His diet is generally balanced, though he sometimes has poor fluid intake, which may worsen constipation and lightheadedness. He remains mostly independent in basic activities of daily living but needs help with some instrumental tasks such as managing appointments and heavier household chores."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
